00:01:45.690 --> 00:01:47.981
JAMES RIGATO: So, yeah, I
got a job on my 14th birthday

00:01:47.981 --> 00:01:50.360
at a local diner in Howell.

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:52.150
I'm not a big fan of
Howell, to be honest.

00:01:52.150 --> 00:01:55.030
It's a pretty
culturally dead town.

00:01:55.030 --> 00:01:56.380
You can't find a piece of fish.

00:01:56.380 --> 00:01:58.930
You can't find a
person of color.

00:01:58.930 --> 00:02:00.800
You can't find
anything interesting.

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:03.410
So I really grew up just--

00:02:03.410 --> 00:02:04.335
I don't know-- hungry.

00:02:04.335 --> 00:02:05.710
That's what I
always tell people.

00:02:05.710 --> 00:02:06.709
I grew up really hungry.

00:02:06.709 --> 00:02:08.756
And legit-- I mean,
I had a single mom.

00:02:08.756 --> 00:02:10.630
And we were on welfare,
and she worked a lot.

00:02:10.630 --> 00:02:13.930
And so my sister and I
were home alone a lot.

00:02:13.930 --> 00:02:17.494
So I just was like
hungry for everything.

00:02:17.494 --> 00:02:20.290
And I think a trait that I
developed young that a lot

00:02:20.290 --> 00:02:21.839
of my friends didn't--

00:02:21.839 --> 00:02:23.380
for instance, I'm
the only kid that--

00:02:23.380 --> 00:02:26.060
I grew up with kind of
posse of four kids, me

00:02:26.060 --> 00:02:27.820
and three other neighbors.

00:02:27.820 --> 00:02:29.840
And they actually had
it worse than I did.

00:02:29.840 --> 00:02:32.230
But I'm the only one that
graduated high school.

00:02:32.230 --> 00:02:34.804
And we moved downtown Howell.

00:02:34.804 --> 00:02:35.970
I grew up in a trailer park.

00:02:35.970 --> 00:02:38.670
We moved downtown Howell into
a house when I was about 12.

00:02:38.670 --> 00:02:41.525
And then I was in
proximity to that diner.

00:02:41.525 --> 00:02:44.369
And that diner kind of like--

00:02:44.369 --> 00:02:45.910
I don't want to say
it saved my life,

00:02:45.910 --> 00:02:47.660
but it kind of shifted things.

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:53.350
I grew up, and I always felt
like trailer park, Howell,

00:02:53.350 --> 00:02:55.364
like mundane things
are temporary.

00:02:55.364 --> 00:02:57.280
I always felt like my
situation was temporary.

00:02:57.280 --> 00:02:59.920
I was like, this
sucks, and I can't

00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:01.980
wait to get over there,
where it doesn't suck.

00:03:01.980 --> 00:03:02.290
JASON ANDREAS:
We're going to have

00:03:02.290 --> 00:03:04.390
to put a disclaimer on
this video for anyone

00:03:04.390 --> 00:03:05.400
watching from Howell.

00:03:05.400 --> 00:03:06.053
So apologies.

00:03:06.053 --> 00:03:07.022
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:07.022 --> 00:03:08.105
Anyone from Howell, it's--

00:03:08.105 --> 00:03:09.040
JAMES RIGATO: It's fine.

00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:10.430
JASON ANDREAS: There's some
decent things there, too.

00:03:10.430 --> 00:03:10.916
JAMES RIGATO: Yeah, yeah.

00:03:10.916 --> 00:03:11.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:11.890 --> 00:03:12.420
JAMES RIGATO: No, I
don't need to say it.

00:03:12.420 --> 00:03:13.560
JASON ANDREAS: Couple
stop lights-- it's good.

00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:14.434
[LAUGHING]

00:03:14.434 --> 00:03:17.210
JAMES RIGATO: But, I mean,
literally think about it.

00:03:17.210 --> 00:03:18.580
You grow up in a town.

00:03:18.580 --> 00:03:21.310
You have no-- there's
just no resources.

00:03:21.310 --> 00:03:22.430
There's no live music.

00:03:22.430 --> 00:03:24.310
There's no art.

00:03:24.310 --> 00:03:26.364
There's no food--
especially food.

00:03:26.364 --> 00:03:28.030
Even right now, go
there and try to eat.

00:03:28.030 --> 00:03:28.821
I mean, it's tough.

00:03:28.821 --> 00:03:30.040
There's no food.

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:34.030
So I always wanted better food.

00:03:34.030 --> 00:03:34.777
I wanted culture.

00:03:34.777 --> 00:03:35.360
I wanted life.

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:39.300
And actually, my dad started
to enroll me in YMCA camps.

00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:42.980
So in the summertime, I'd go
away for two weeks at a time,

00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:46.300
and I'd go up to Camp Nissokone
in the middle of Oscoda.

00:03:46.300 --> 00:03:50.570
And there were kids all
over Detroit and Michigan,

00:03:50.570 --> 00:03:53.740
counselors from Africa
and South America.

00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:57.110
And literally, I remember
watching one of our counselors,

00:03:57.110 --> 00:04:00.010
this African dude from Kenya,
cooking potatoes over the fire

00:04:00.010 --> 00:04:01.260
and like butter and bacon fat.

00:04:01.260 --> 00:04:04.487
And stuff like that
was really the things

00:04:04.487 --> 00:04:05.570
that stood out in my mind.

00:04:05.570 --> 00:04:07.319
I'm like, man, here's
all these people

00:04:07.319 --> 00:04:09.610
from different walks of life,
and we're over this fire,

00:04:09.610 --> 00:04:11.470
and we're cooking
potatoes from raw.

00:04:11.470 --> 00:04:12.960
We all can connect
with that potato

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:15.360
regardless of where
we're all from.

00:04:15.360 --> 00:04:18.430
So just things like that stood
out so I got a job at 14.

00:04:18.430 --> 00:04:21.075
Actually, if anyone knows Rose's
Fine Foods down in Detroit,

00:04:21.075 --> 00:04:22.780
so that's Molly
Mitchell's restaurant.

00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:24.946
Molly Mitchell went to the
same high school as me,

00:04:24.946 --> 00:04:26.030
and actually elementary school.

00:04:26.030 --> 00:04:27.071
I've known Molly forever.

00:04:27.071 --> 00:04:28.190
Molly actually called me.

00:04:28.190 --> 00:04:30.000
She's like, yo, I
know you're 14 now.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:31.083
You can work at the diner.

00:04:31.083 --> 00:04:32.470
Come down and get a job here.

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:33.220
So I did.

00:04:33.220 --> 00:04:34.230
I got a job.

00:04:34.230 --> 00:04:36.179
I just washed dishes,
and it sucked.

00:04:36.179 --> 00:04:37.470
It was like the worst job ever.

00:04:37.470 --> 00:04:39.700
And I ended up getting a
job at Papa John's flipping

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:41.510
pizzas instead.

00:04:41.510 --> 00:04:42.690
But that was kind of like--

00:04:42.690 --> 00:04:46.060
that day one, washing
pots and pans--

00:04:46.060 --> 00:04:48.290
and it was a 24-hour diner,
so it never shut down,

00:04:48.290 --> 00:04:53.010
and I went home, and my fingers
were all pruned, and I'm tired.

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:54.880
I'm was like, man,
I got purpose.

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:58.210
I felt like I had
purpose all of a sudden.

00:04:58.210 --> 00:04:59.230
And then you got paid.

00:04:59.230 --> 00:05:01.140
And I was like, oh my god.

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:04.250
Growing up poor, we used
to walk to the party store

00:05:04.250 --> 00:05:06.479
and collect bottles on the way.

00:05:06.479 --> 00:05:08.770
And you get in the party
store with a buck, 10 bottles,

00:05:08.770 --> 00:05:11.310
and you're like, dude,
that's like a beef jerky

00:05:11.310 --> 00:05:13.660
or whatever, a Whatchamacallit
and a Mountain Dew.

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:17.620
So once I started getting
paid for washing dishes,

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:21.030
and then I got a job at Papa
John's making $6.50 an hour,

00:05:21.030 --> 00:05:21.804
I was like, psht--

00:05:21.804 --> 00:05:22.580
I'm ballin'.

00:05:22.580 --> 00:05:26.730
For Like 18 hours a week, like,
oh, my god, are you kidding me?

00:05:26.730 --> 00:05:29.620
That's like $100 a week
I can probably make.

00:05:29.620 --> 00:05:31.430
And so then I got a
job at a restaurant.

00:05:31.430 --> 00:05:33.436
Because one girl in
my class was like, yo,

00:05:33.436 --> 00:05:35.019
we need a pizza guy
at our restaurant.

00:05:35.019 --> 00:05:36.450
I said, I can make pizza.

00:05:36.450 --> 00:05:37.840
Went to that restaurants.

00:05:37.840 --> 00:05:38.580
I was 16.

00:05:38.580 --> 00:05:41.740
And I could make pizza
better than anybody there,

00:05:41.740 --> 00:05:43.510
but that's when
I saw line cooks.

00:05:43.510 --> 00:05:44.800
That's when I saw a chef.

00:05:44.800 --> 00:05:47.240
I saw a dude in white checks.

00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:49.053
Checks are like the chef pants.

00:05:49.053 --> 00:05:51.660
And I was like, oh, that guy
is a chef, like for a living?

00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:53.010
Like that's what he
does for a living?

00:05:53.010 --> 00:05:53.884
He's a grown-ass man.

00:05:53.884 --> 00:05:55.324
He's got kids--
like, oh, my god.

00:05:55.324 --> 00:05:55.824
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:55.824 --> 00:05:57.160
And then I saw the cooks.

00:05:57.160 --> 00:05:59.230
And now you look
back at these cooks,

00:05:59.230 --> 00:06:03.190
and they're like 23-year-old,
drugged-out bums.

00:06:03.190 --> 00:06:06.715
But then, I was like,
these dudes are flipping

00:06:06.715 --> 00:06:09.010
and like hitting each other
with tongs on the butt

00:06:09.010 --> 00:06:13.380
and lighting hands on fire
and just like spinning shit,

00:06:13.380 --> 00:06:15.080
pulling off tickets.

00:06:15.080 --> 00:06:16.720
You used to put a
plate in the window,

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:20.120
and you put enough English on
to where it goes to topple over

00:06:20.120 --> 00:06:21.350
but spins back.

00:06:21.350 --> 00:06:23.310
I was just like, bfft!

00:06:23.310 --> 00:06:26.340
I couldn't see straight.

00:06:26.340 --> 00:06:28.920
And so about six
months into that job--

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:31.477
I'm like almost 17, 16--

00:06:31.477 --> 00:06:32.185
grill cook quits.

00:06:32.185 --> 00:06:35.410
This dude AJ, choked out
Caveman-- the saute cook,

00:06:35.410 --> 00:06:36.155
we called him.

00:06:36.155 --> 00:06:37.820
He choked out
Caveman on the line.

00:06:37.820 --> 00:06:39.548
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:39.548 --> 00:06:41.170
And I'm like, damn,
this guy's crazy.

00:06:41.170 --> 00:06:42.280
And AJ quits.

00:06:42.280 --> 00:06:44.834
Chef was a nice guy,
but he sure as shit

00:06:44.834 --> 00:06:46.750
was not going to get on
that hotline and cook.

00:06:46.750 --> 00:06:49.840
He was like 40, and they're
always drugged-out cooks

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:51.640
doing 600 covers a night.

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:53.190
He's like, you!

00:06:53.190 --> 00:06:54.670
He's like, Jimmy, can you cook?

00:06:54.670 --> 00:06:55.590
I'm like, yeah, I can do it.

00:06:55.590 --> 00:06:57.173
I've been watching
him for six months.

00:06:57.173 --> 00:07:01.480
Went on the grill, banged-out
grill, and killed the night

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:02.696
service.

00:07:02.696 --> 00:07:04.820
The owner comes over, and
he's like, I'm lead cook.

00:07:04.820 --> 00:07:06.190
You're the new grill cook.

00:07:06.190 --> 00:07:07.210
OK.

00:07:07.210 --> 00:07:09.335
So grill cook is a big position.

00:07:09.335 --> 00:07:11.390
It was like 45 hours a week.

00:07:11.390 --> 00:07:12.530
I just get the schedule.

00:07:12.530 --> 00:07:14.650
But I don't know if they
just forgot I was 16 or

00:07:14.650 --> 00:07:16.110
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:16.110 --> 00:07:17.476
But 45 hours a week.

00:07:17.476 --> 00:07:18.767
Like they schedule you at 2:00.

00:07:18.767 --> 00:07:21.105
Well, OK, well, class
gets out at 2:40.

00:07:21.105 --> 00:07:25.270
So like sixth hour, Mr.
O, I was like, Mr. O,

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:28.187
can I go to art class and paint
if I finish my homework early?

00:07:28.187 --> 00:07:29.270
He's like, yeah, OK, cool.

00:07:29.270 --> 00:07:30.840
I had three hours of art.

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:31.716
So he was like, yeah.

00:07:31.716 --> 00:07:32.215
OK.

00:07:32.215 --> 00:07:34.520
I literally finished my
homework and just get in my car

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:36.970
and go to work,
punch in at 2:00,

00:07:36.970 --> 00:07:40.120
close down at 12:00 midnight.

00:07:40.120 --> 00:07:42.518
Bring back a pitcher of
beers in the kitchen.

00:07:42.518 --> 00:07:43.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:43.850 --> 00:07:44.850
The guy hands me a beer.

00:07:44.850 --> 00:07:47.230
I swear to God the
dudes forgot I was 16.

00:07:47.230 --> 00:07:49.260
So I just started working.

00:07:49.260 --> 00:07:52.760
And I stated dating a waitress
who was much older than me.

00:07:52.760 --> 00:07:55.135
And she eventually
found out [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:55.135 --> 00:07:57.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:57.510 --> 00:07:58.450
But that just like--

00:07:58.450 --> 00:08:01.060
I just immediately-- and
then I was making like--

00:08:01.060 --> 00:08:02.770
I don't know-- $10
an hour, $11 an hour.

00:08:02.770 --> 00:08:05.330
I eventually got a
raise to like $11.50.

00:08:05.330 --> 00:08:08.560
I moved out after I
graduated high school at 17.

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:11.194
I tried getting an apartment
but couldn't sign a lease.

00:08:11.194 --> 00:08:12.610
But I had like
four grand in cash.

00:08:12.610 --> 00:08:14.859
So I was like, can I just
pay for six months up front?

00:08:14.859 --> 00:08:17.600
This was the village in Wixom
if anyone knows where that's at.

00:08:17.600 --> 00:08:20.020
One of the whole complexes
was burned down at the time.

00:08:20.020 --> 00:08:22.353
And so I think they were like,
we'll take it-- whatever.

00:08:22.353 --> 00:08:24.890
So I just gave six months'
rent, they gave me the key,

00:08:24.890 --> 00:08:25.870
and I had an apartment.

00:08:25.870 --> 00:08:31.280
So 17, apartment, I'm making
like $11.50, $12 an hour, 50,

00:08:31.280 --> 00:08:34.084
60 hours a week,
enrolled in Schoolcraft.

00:08:34.084 --> 00:08:36.539
And I just was entrenched.

00:08:36.539 --> 00:08:38.159
That's really my
jump-start, I think.

00:08:38.159 --> 00:08:40.120
Because I opened a
restaurant at 26.

00:08:40.120 --> 00:08:41.890
I graduated from
culinary school at 20.

00:08:41.890 --> 00:08:44.290
All day long, I got people
that come to my restaurant,

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:48.750
even now, as recent as last
night, oh, you're baby face.

00:08:48.750 --> 00:08:50.920
You're so-- how old are you?

00:08:50.920 --> 00:08:52.040
Where's your dad at?

00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:53.636
Where's the chef?

00:08:53.636 --> 00:08:54.510
I'm 32.

00:08:54.510 --> 00:08:55.720
I'm young.

00:08:55.720 --> 00:08:56.700
I've been doing this--

00:08:56.700 --> 00:08:57.658
I've been on the grind.

00:08:57.658 --> 00:09:02.740
I've been standing on
quarry tile under UV lights,

00:09:02.740 --> 00:09:04.910
banging pans, for 18 years.

00:09:04.910 --> 00:09:06.380
I could be a fucking surgeon.

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:08.530
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:08.530 --> 00:09:13.540
So to me, that's the
industry in a nutshell.

00:09:13.540 --> 00:09:17.170
And that's how I started,
banging pans, drinking beers,

00:09:17.170 --> 00:09:18.930
just being the man.

00:09:18.930 --> 00:09:21.910
But then at Schoolcraft,
I was like, oh, shit.

00:09:21.910 --> 00:09:24.080
There's actually finesse, right?

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:25.400
There's knowledge.

00:09:25.400 --> 00:09:27.820
There's like, OK,
this is a profession.

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:33.630
This is as distinguished as
politics or the fine arts.

00:09:33.630 --> 00:09:35.710
This is ballet.

