I was the dirty kid
in Catholic school.

00:12:13.246 --> 00:12:15.490
But I was the Catholic
kid in the neighborhood.

00:12:15.490 --> 00:12:18.120
So I was always juxtaposed.

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:21.000
I was either like a prissy punk
or like a dirtbag trailer park

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:22.410
kid.

00:12:22.410 --> 00:12:23.229
I couldn't find--

00:12:23.229 --> 00:12:25.020
Which actually kind of
fits, because that's

00:12:25.020 --> 00:12:27.400
kind of what Mabel Gray
is, honestly, right?

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:29.720
We're the fancy
restaurant in Hazel Park.

00:12:29.720 --> 00:12:31.142
But if you like
fancy restaurants,

00:12:31.142 --> 00:12:33.100
we're like the grungy,
piece-of-shit restaurant

00:12:33.100 --> 00:12:35.790
that plays Tupac while
you eat a tasting meal.

00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:38.110
So that's been my identity.

00:12:38.110 --> 00:12:40.470
I enjoy that.

00:12:40.470 --> 00:12:42.160
Now I love it.

00:12:42.160 --> 00:12:44.590
But then it was like my paradox.

00:12:44.590 --> 00:12:47.710
But I think it's very important
to pay attention to food.

00:12:47.710 --> 00:12:50.520
Food is so much purpose.

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:51.840
Like if you look at France--

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:53.400
I've spent a lot
of time in France.

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:56.651
France is kind of a
culture of arrogance.

00:12:56.651 --> 00:12:57.150
It just is.

00:12:57.150 --> 00:12:59.540
I'm not mad at France,
but they're very proud.

00:12:59.540 --> 00:13:01.850
If you're in France, you're
on the Basque border,

00:13:01.850 --> 00:13:03.510
they don't cook Spanish food.

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:05.957
But go on a train, go 30
minutes, go eat Spanish.

00:13:05.957 --> 00:13:06.540
You're French.

00:13:06.540 --> 00:13:08.260
We eat French food.

00:13:08.260 --> 00:13:11.190
Whereas us, we're like,
dude, go to Windsor.

00:13:11.190 --> 00:13:12.790
Go check out Little Italy.

00:13:12.790 --> 00:13:14.880
We'll give you
advice where to eat.

00:13:14.880 --> 00:13:16.510
Oh, you should go over to the
Western side of the state.

00:13:16.510 --> 00:13:17.260
Go to [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:17.260 --> 00:13:18.030
Go to Chicago.

00:13:18.030 --> 00:13:19.320
We all love Chicago.

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:22.490
Live There it's
like, Spain is crap.

00:13:22.490 --> 00:13:23.860
This is the best.

00:13:23.860 --> 00:13:25.620
But think about it, man.

00:13:25.620 --> 00:13:27.890
This is a country
that's-- how many wars--

00:13:27.890 --> 00:13:30.180
look at Champagne, the region.

00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:34.010
Every single war from France
has trampled through Champagne.

00:13:34.010 --> 00:13:37.050
And there's a bloody,
sad, bleak history

00:13:37.050 --> 00:13:39.970
of that-- we all think of
Champagne, pop the cork, party.

00:13:39.970 --> 00:13:40.996
Go to Champagne.

00:13:40.996 --> 00:13:42.870
Pay attention to the
history and the culture.

00:13:42.870 --> 00:13:43.369
It's flat.

00:13:43.369 --> 00:13:45.150
There's no mountains, right?

00:13:45.150 --> 00:13:51.040
It is the highway of invasion,
from the Vikings to Hitler.

00:13:51.040 --> 00:13:54.294
Everybody has trampled through
that part of-- in the world.

00:13:54.294 --> 00:13:58.475
So I think of Champagne,
yes, I pop champagne.

00:13:58.475 --> 00:13:59.600
It's New Year's-- whatever.

00:13:59.600 --> 00:14:03.385
But when I drink champagne,
I look at that bottle, fuck,

00:14:03.385 --> 00:14:04.420
man, like the history--

00:14:04.420 --> 00:14:09.870
Champagne is so important and
so serious in the world, right?

00:14:09.870 --> 00:14:11.047
Like they set the bar.

00:14:11.047 --> 00:14:12.880
If you have great
sparkling wine from Italy,

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:15.690
if you have great
Schramsberg from California,

00:14:15.690 --> 00:14:16.970
they do a champagne method.

00:14:16.970 --> 00:14:19.140
They label it "Champagne
method" because they let

00:14:19.140 --> 00:14:22.100
you know they set the standard.

00:14:22.100 --> 00:14:22.959
So I don't know.

00:14:22.959 --> 00:14:24.750
If you're just like,
let's order champagne,

00:14:24.750 --> 00:14:28.835
or they call American sparkling
wine champagne, I'm like--

00:14:28.835 --> 00:14:30.668
I can talk about Champagne
for fucking days.

00:14:30.668 --> 00:14:32.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:32.540 --> 00:14:35.130
So with food, it's important
to remember that, too.

00:14:35.130 --> 00:14:38.690
American culture, we
barely create much.

00:14:38.690 --> 00:14:40.210
We kind of just lift it, right.

00:14:40.210 --> 00:14:41.587
You look at soul food.

00:14:41.587 --> 00:14:42.810
You look at barbecue.

00:14:42.810 --> 00:14:46.030
How much bad white-boy
barbecue does Michigan need?

00:14:46.030 --> 00:14:48.516
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:48.516 --> 00:14:50.432
JASON ANDREAS: We haven't
hit the ceiling yet.

00:14:50.432 --> 00:14:52.130
JAMES RIGATO: Yeah, you
haven't seen nothing yet.

00:14:52.130 --> 00:14:53.260
There's probably like 20 more
barbecue restaurants opening up

00:14:53.260 --> 00:14:55.130
in the next two years.

00:14:55.130 --> 00:14:57.060
There's so much bad
barbecue in this state.

00:14:57.060 --> 00:14:59.970
And even the good
barbecue, they buy

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:03.510
the shit at Restaurant Depot,
add sugar and salt in, then

00:15:03.510 --> 00:15:04.650
smoke it for 24 hours.

00:15:04.650 --> 00:15:07.610
It's like candy.

00:15:07.610 --> 00:15:10.680
Like barbecue is such a
serious cuisine for me.

00:15:10.680 --> 00:15:13.230
Because, for one, the
real barbecue out there

00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:16.500
is like a heritage pig, right?

00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:20.040
You pick your pig, you butcher
it, it's whole roasted,

00:15:20.040 --> 00:15:21.470
it's broken down.

00:15:21.470 --> 00:15:25.360
Usually the cook is up with it
all night, tending the fire,

00:15:25.360 --> 00:15:27.360
loving in the process.

00:15:27.360 --> 00:15:30.240
Next morning, lunchtime, you
break down the whole pig.

00:15:30.240 --> 00:15:32.130
You serve it till it's out.

00:15:32.130 --> 00:15:33.310
Barbecue is done.

00:15:33.310 --> 00:15:35.190
That's barbecue.

00:15:35.190 --> 00:15:38.610
400 pounds of just
one cut of the--

00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:41.810
400 pounds of brisket is
like, whatever, like 20 cows,

00:15:41.810 --> 00:15:43.920
but just like one
part of 20 cows.

00:15:43.920 --> 00:15:45.876
So like it's a
2,000-pound animal.

00:15:45.876 --> 00:15:48.210
You're going to take a
10-pound chunk of it and say,

00:15:48.210 --> 00:15:49.740
who gives a shit about the rest?

00:15:49.740 --> 00:15:52.850
Rub it down with sugar and
then smoke it, then slice

00:15:52.850 --> 00:15:54.600
and be like, I'm the man?

00:15:54.600 --> 00:15:57.450
I don't get that.

00:15:57.450 --> 00:16:03.960
Barbecue is like the off cuts,
open flame, or whole animal,

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:07.070
local proximity to
farms, nurturing,

00:16:07.070 --> 00:16:09.250
using vinegar and
sugar and spices

00:16:09.250 --> 00:16:13.980
to manipulate the
tougher, fattier, not

00:16:13.980 --> 00:16:18.020
like center-table kind
of cuts and cooking it

00:16:18.020 --> 00:16:20.710
for people of the Earth,
hand-to-mouth people.

00:16:20.710 --> 00:16:22.860
So it's lifted from
the West Indies.

00:16:22.860 --> 00:16:26.160
It's lifted from
history of slaves.

00:16:26.160 --> 00:16:29.190
Barbecue is a very
serious cuisine for me.

00:16:29.190 --> 00:16:34.890
So I don't like the, like I
said, strip-mall, shitty, fast,

00:16:34.890 --> 00:16:40.590
sugar, cheap junk, get the
fat people fatter mentality.

00:16:40.590 --> 00:16:41.760
It bothers me.

00:16:41.760 --> 00:16:45.660
So I could talk about
barbecue for days.

00:16:45.660 --> 00:16:46.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:46.160 --> 00:16:47.280
So that's what food
had done for me.

00:16:47.280 --> 00:16:48.363
It's created this purpose.

00:16:48.363 --> 00:16:51.470
Food is this living
history, right?

00:16:51.470 --> 00:16:53.320
I think when robots
take over the world,

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:57.810
and there's robots cooking,
they're still not going do it--

00:16:57.810 --> 00:17:00.330
it's one of the protected arts.

00:17:00.330 --> 00:17:02.280
Google is an interesting
company because where

00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:03.980
was it 20 years ago?

00:17:03.980 --> 00:17:05.730
Where is it going to
be 20 years from now?

00:17:05.730 --> 00:17:07.104
So many questions--
I think there

00:17:07.104 --> 00:17:09.262
are more questions
about the tech industry

00:17:09.262 --> 00:17:10.220
than there are answers.

00:17:10.220 --> 00:17:13.260
Whereas the food, I feel
like there's more history

00:17:13.260 --> 00:17:16.201
than there is future.

00:17:16.201 --> 00:17:18.700
You want to think about forward,
you've got to go backwards.

00:17:18.700 --> 00:17:21.420
You've got to look at
where everything came from.

00:17:21.420 --> 00:17:23.800
If anything, we're running
into trouble with food, right?

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:25.050
We're going to run out of it--

00:17:25.050 --> 00:17:30.880
GMOs, like fishing-- oh, my
god, what sushi restaurants

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:32.550
have done to the world.

00:17:32.550 --> 00:17:35.630
So I think we need to think
about food holistically

00:17:35.630 --> 00:17:38.300
and who we are as a people.

00:17:38.300 --> 00:17:41.486
Wasn't it
Brillat-Savarin, show me

00:17:41.486 --> 00:17:43.510
what you eat, I'll
show you who you are?

00:17:43.510 --> 00:17:45.100
JASON ANDREAS: Yeah.

00:17:45.100 --> 00:17:47.920
JAMES RIGATO: So that's
what food is to me.

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:49.650
Mabel Gray is obviously
just a restaurant

00:17:49.650 --> 00:17:51.890
in a neighborhood-- you
can say whatever you want,

00:17:51.890 --> 00:17:55.050
gentrifying or
pop redevelopment.

00:17:55.050 --> 00:17:57.880
But to me, we were
talking about earlier,

00:17:57.880 --> 00:17:59.910
Mabel Gray is a blank canvas.

00:17:59.910 --> 00:18:02.730
It's like a little art
gallery for me and my friends.

00:18:02.730 --> 00:18:04.532
And maybe I'm passionate
about barbecue.

00:18:04.532 --> 00:18:06.990
Maybe I'll get a whole pig and
I want to do barbecue night.

00:18:06.990 --> 00:18:10.080
And maybe I want to
focus on the West Indies

00:18:10.080 --> 00:18:14.280
or show my cooks why a certain
technique is important.

00:18:14.280 --> 00:18:16.610
Or my farmer has 16 rabbits.

00:18:16.610 --> 00:18:20.047
Well, then we're going to play
with rabbits for a couple days.

00:18:20.047 --> 00:18:20.880
It's a living space.

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:26.850
To me it's like my best attempt
to curate the purpose of food

00:18:26.850 --> 00:18:28.166
in metro Detroit.

00:18:28.166 --> 00:18:28.680
JASON ANDREAS: Well,
obviously there's

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:31.290
a lot of care that goes into
your menu on a nightly basis.

